# WordPress REST API Standards

Use REST, not `admin-ajax.php`. Register routes on `rest_api_init`.

## Route registration pattern

```php
register_rest_route( 'my-plugin/v1', '/items/(?P<id>\d+)', [
    [
        'methods'             => WP_REST_Server::READABLE,
        'callback'            => 'my_plugin_get_item',
        'permission_callback' => static function ( $req ) {
            $post = get_post( (int) $req['id'] );
            return $post && ( 'publish' === $post->post_status || current_user_can( 'read_post', $post->ID ) );
        },
        'args' => [
            'id' => [ 'type' => 'integer', 'required' => true, 'sanitize_callback' => 'absint' ],
        ],
    ],
    [
        'methods'             => WP_REST_Server::CREATABLE,
        'callback'            => 'my_plugin_update_item',
        'permission_callback' => static fn() => current_user_can( 'edit_posts' ),
        'args' => [
            'title' => [
                'type' => 'string', 'required' => true,
                'sanitize_callback' => 'sanitize_text_field',
                'validate_callback' => static fn( $v ) => is_string( $v ) && strlen( $v ) <= 200,
            ],
        ],
    ],
] );
```

## Rules

- Namespace routes (`my-plugin/v1`). Bump version for breaking changes.
- Use `WP_REST_Server` constants (`READABLE`, `CREATABLE`, `EDITABLE`, `DELETABLE`), not string literals.
- Provide `args` with `type`, `required`, `sanitize_callback`, `validate_callback`.
- `permission_callback` is required. `__return_true` only for public read-only endpoints — document why.
- Return `WP_REST_Response` or `WP_Error` with proper HTTP status.
- Shape data via `prepare_item_for_response` — don't leak internal structure.
- Never mutate state on GET.
- Never return 200 with `{"error": "..."}` — use the right status code + `WP_Error`.

## JS side — @wordpress/api-fetch

```js
import apiFetch from '@wordpress/api-fetch';

// GET
const items = await apiFetch( { path: '/my-plugin/v1/items' } );

// POST
await apiFetch( {
    path: '/my-plugin/v1/items/42',
    method: 'POST',
    data: { title: 'New' },
} );
```

`api-fetch` auto-attaches `X-WP-Nonce` for cookie auth. For external clients use Application Passwords.

## Schema definition

```php
'schema' => [
    '$schema'    => 'http://json-schema.org/draft-04/schema#',
    'title'      => 'my-plugin-item',
    'type'       => 'object',
    'properties' => [
        'id'    => [ 'type' => 'integer', 'readonly' => true ],
        'title' => [ 'type' => 'string' ],
        'status'=> [ 'type' => 'string', 'enum' => [ 'active', 'archived' ] ],
    ],
],
```

## Things to avoid

1. **No permission callback** — WordPress will reject the route entirely (5.5+)
2. **Returning raw DB rows** — always shape and sanitize the response
3. **Ignoring WP_Error** — check `is_wp_error()` on internal calls before returning
4. **String method names** — use `WP_REST_Server::READABLE` not `'GET'`
5. **Missing arg validation** — every arg should have `type` + `sanitize_callback` at minimum
